## Abstract

This meta-analysis investigates the relationship between structural brain connectivity, as measured by diffusion MRI (dMRI) metrics, and individual music preferences. We synthesized findings from multiple studies to determine whether specific white matter tracts show consistent associations with musical preferences. {% if result.get('synthesis_mode') == 'quantitative' %}A random-effects meta-analysis was performed on {{ result.study_count }} eligible studies.{% else %}Due to limited study availability (N < 10), a qualitative narrative synthesis was conducted.{% endif %}

## Introduction

Music preference is a complex psychological trait influenced by cognitive, emotional, and social factors. Recent neuroimaging research has suggested that individual differences in music preferences may be associated with variations in structural brain connectivity. This meta-analysis aims to aggregate evidence across studies to identify robust associations between specific white matter tracts and music preference behaviors.

